Recap-

Containers = package the source code of an app and it’s dependancies into a lightweight portable container to used on different machines

VM’s 
- Are like fully computers with its own operating system 
- Sits in-between hardware and vm’s = hypervisor 
- Using the hypervisor it emulates the hardware ( virtualisation ) for each VM 
- Running on a single physical machine (resource heavy ) (heavier) (but offer stronger isolation)

Containers
- Runs containers on the host OS 
- Share the same OS (lightweight)
- Has the app and it’s dependancies - like binaries and libraries  



Docker vs K8? 

Docker - runs containers and you manage them manually 

K8 - orchestrates everything
- where the containers run 
- Automatically scaling containers up and down 
- Makes sure containers are packed efficiently into nodes ( machines )



What is k8 and why we use it ? 

- System that automates how we handle containerised apps 
- Originally came from google 
- Makes sure these containers are put on machines ( nodes ) - scaling up and down 
- K8 also replaces containers that fail in machines nodes 
- K8 also handles things like load balancing , storage and updates 
- Orchestrates everything 



Enterprises and the changes they adopted ?

Enterprises got tired of slow deployments so they adopted using micro services 
-  Microservices  ( breaking app into separate functions/ services )
- These microservices can be developed , deployed and scaled independently 

But even when they put apps were put into containers they needed a tool to orchestrate them 
- K8’s steer and orchestrates these containers 
